# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: advocaat
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The once Celtic settlement was equipped with several *thermae* in the course of colonization by Roman pioneers settling at the warm Aachen thermal springs around the 1st century.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] After the withdrawal of the Roman troops, the vicus *Aquae Granni* was Frankized around the 5th century, by which it came under Merovingian and later Carolingian rule.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] With the completion of the Carolingian Palace of Aachen at the transition to the 9th century, Aachen was constituted as the main royal residence of the Frankish Empire ruled by Charlemagne.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Because of that, the city is sometimes called the "cradle of Europe".
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] After the Treaty of Verdun, the city was within the borders of Middle Francia, until it became part of East Francia after the Treaty of Meerssen (870).
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] It subsequently was part of the Holy Roman Empire and was granted city rights in 1166 by Emperor Frederick Barbarossa, becoming an imperial city.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] It served as the coronation site where 31 Holy Roman Emperors were crowned Kings of the Germans from 936 to 1531, until Frankfurt became the preferred place of coronation.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] One of Germany's leading institutes of higher education in technology, the RWTH Aachen University *(Rheinisch-Westfälisch Technische Hochschule Aachen)*, is located in the city.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Its university hospital Uniklinikum Aachen is Europe's largest single-building hospital.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Aachen's industries include science, engineering and information technology.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] In 2009, Aachen was ranked eighth among cities in Germany for innovation.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Aachen is located at the northern foothills of the High Fens and the Eifel Mountains.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] It sits on the Wurm River, a tributary of the Rur, and together with Mönchengladbach, it is the only larger German city in the drainage basin of the Meuse.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The regional dialect spoken in the city is a Central Franconian, Ripuarian variant with strong Limburgish influences from the dialects in the neighbouring Netherlands.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] As a Rhenish city, Aachen is one of the main centres of carnival celebrations in Germany, along with Cologne and Mainz.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The culinary specialty for which the city is best known is Aachener Printen, a type of gingerbread.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The name *Aachen* is a modern descendant, like southern German *Ach(e)*, German: *Aach*, meaning "river" or "stream", from Old High German *ahha*, meaning "water" or "stream", which directly translates (and etymologically corresponds) to Latin *Aquae*, referring to the springs.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The location has been inhabited by humans since the Neolithic era, about 5,000 years ago, attracted to its warm mineral springs.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Latin *Aquae* figures in Aachen's Roman name *Aquae granni*, which meant "waters of Grannus", referring to the Celtic god of healing who was worshipped at the springs.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] This word became *Åxhe* in Walloon and *Aix* in French, and subsequently *Aix-la-Chapelle* to distinguish it from Aix-en-Provence, after Charlemagne had his palatine chapel built there in the late 8th century and then made the city his empire's capital.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Flint quarries on the Lousberg, Schneeberg, and Königshügel, first used during Neolithic times (3000–2500 BC), attest to the long occupation of the site of Aachen, as do recent finds under the modern city's *Elisengarten* pointing to a former settlement from the same period.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Bronze Age (around 1600 BC) settlement is evidenced by the remains of barrows (burial mounds) found, for example, on the Klausberg.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] During the Iron Age, the area was settled by Celtic peoples who were perhaps drawn by the marshy Aachen basin's hot sulphur springs where they worshipped Grannus, god of light and healing.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Proofs of a Celts settlements on Aachens territories at the beginning of the Gallic War do not exist at the moment.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The 25-hectare Roman spa resort town of Aquae Granni was, according to legend, founded by Grenus, under Hadrian, around 124 AD.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Grenus refers to the Celtic god, and it seems it was the Roman 6th Legion at the start of the 1st century AD that first channelled the hot springs into a spa at Büchel, adding at the end of the same century the *Münstertherme* spa, two water pipelines, and a probable sanctuary dedicated to Grannus.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] A kind of forum, surrounded by colonnades, connected the two spa complexes.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] There was an extensive residential area.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The Romans built bathhouses near Burtscheid.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] A temple precinct called *Vernenum* was built near the modern Kornelimünster/Walheim.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Today, remains have been found of three bathhouses, including two fountains in the *Elisenbrunnen* and the Burtscheid bathhouse.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Roman civil administration in Aachen eventually broke down as the baths and other public buildings (along with most of the villae rusticae of the surrounding countryside) were destroyed around AD 375 at the start of the migration period.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The last Roman coin finds are from the time of Emperor Gratian (AD 375–383).
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Rome withdrew its troops from the area, but the town remained populated.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] By 470, the town came to be ruled by the Ripuarian Franks and subordinated to their capital, Cologne.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] During the Roman period, Aachen was the site of a flourishing Jewish community.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Pepin the Short had a castle residence built in the town, due to the proximity of the hot springs and also for strategic reasons as it is located between the Rhineland and northern France.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] In the year of his coronation as king of the Franks, 768, Charlemagne came to spend Christmas at Aachen for the first time.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] He remained there in a mansion which he may have extended, although there is no source attesting to any significant building activity at Aachen in his time, apart from the building of the Palatine Chapel (since 1930, cathedral) and the Palace.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Charlemagne spent most winters in Aachen between 792 and his death in 814.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Aachen became the focus of his court and the political centre of his empire.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] During the Carolingian empire, a Jewish community lived near the royal palace.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] In Jewish texts, the city of Aachen was called *Aish* or *Ash* (אש).
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] In 797, Isaac, a Jewish merchant, accompanied two ambassadors of Charlemagne to the court of Harun al-Rashid.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] He returned to Aachen in July 802, bearing an elephant called Abul-Abbas as a gift for the emperor.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] By the terms of the Treaty of Verdun 834, Aachen became part of Middle Francia, governed by emperor Lothair.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] He was succeeded by Lothair II as king of Lotharingia by the terms of the Treaty of Prüm.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] By the Treaty of Meerssen 870, Aachen came to East Francia.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Within East Francia, later the Holy Roman Empire until 1166, Aachen was part of the Duchy of Lower Lotharingia.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] In 936, Otto I was crowned king of East Francia in the collegiate church built by Charlemagne.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] During the reign of Otto II, the nobles revolted and the West Franks under Lothair raided Aachen in 978.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Aachen was attacked again by Odo of Champagne, who attacked the imperial palace while Conrad II was absent.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Odo relinquished it and was killed afterwards.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The palace and town of Aachen had fortifying walls built by order of Emperor Frederick Barbarossa between 1172 and 1176.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Over the next 500 years, most kings of Germany who ruled the Holy Roman Empire were crowned in Aachen.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The original audience hall built by Charlemagne was torn down and replaced by the current city hall in 1330.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] During the 13th century, many Jews converted to Christianity, as shown in the records of the Aachen Minster (today's Cathedral).
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] In 1486, the Jews of Aachen offered gifts to Maximilian I during his coronation ceremony.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The last king to be crowned here was Ferdinand I in 1531.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] During the Middle Ages, Aachen remained a city of regional importance, due to its proximity to Flanders; it achieved a modest position in the trade in woollen cloths, favoured by imperial privilege.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The city remained a free imperial city, subject to the emperor only, but was politically far too weak to influence the policies of any of its neighbours.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The only dominion it had was over Burtscheid, a neighbouring territory ruled by a Benedictine abbess, which was forced to accept that all of its traffic must pass through the "Aachener Reich".
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] As an imperial city, Aachen held certain political privileges that allowed it to remain independent of the troubles of Europe for many years.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] It remained a direct vassal of the Holy Roman Empire throughout most of the Middle Ages.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] It was also the site of many important church councils, including the Council of 837 and the Council of 1166, a council convened by the antipope Paschal III.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Parts of Aachen belonged to Imperial Abbey of Burtscheid, Reichsabtei Kornelimünster, Duchy of Juelich and the Duchy of Limburg.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Aachen was an important site for the production of historical manuscripts.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Under Charlemagne's purview, both the Ada Gospels and the Coronation Gospels may have been produced in Aachen.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] In addition, quantities of the other texts in the court library were also produced locally.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] During the reign of Louis the Pious (814–840), substantial quantities of ancient texts were produced at Aachen, including legal manuscripts such as the leges scriptorium group, patristic texts including the five manuscripts of the Bamberg Pliny Group.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Finally, under Lothair I (840–855), texts of outstanding quality were still being produced.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] This however marked the end of the period of manuscript production at Aachen.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] In 1598, following the invasion of Spanish troops from the Netherlands, Rudolf deposed all Protestant office holders in Aachen and went as far as expelling them from the city.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] From the early 16th century, Aachen started to lose its power and influence.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] First the coronations of emperors were moved from Aachen to Frankfurt.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] 1614 Aachen became theatre of the Siege of Aachen (1614) within the War of the Jülich Succession.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Although religious changes were forced several times in Aachen and Protestant communities were banned, hardly any fighting took place during the Thirty Years' War.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The religious wars had been followed by the great fire of 1656.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] After the destruction of most of the city in 1656, the rebuilding was mostly in the Baroque style.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The decline of Aachen culminated in 1794, when the French, led by General Charles Dumouriez, occupied Aachen..
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The area of Aachen had been scene of battles within the Flanders Campaign in autumn 1794: Battle of Ourthe, Battle of Aldenhoven, Siege of Maastricht.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] In 1542, the Dutch humanist and physician Francis Fabricius published his study of the health benefits of the hot springs in Aachen.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] By the middle of the 17th century, the city had developed a considerable reputation as a spa, although this was in part because Aachen was then – and remained well into the 19th and early 20th century – a place of high-level prostitution.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Traces of this hidden agenda of the city's history are found in the 18th-century guidebooks to Aachen as well as to the other spas.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The main indication for visiting patients, ironically, was syphilis; only by the end of the 19th century had rheumatism become the most important object of cures at Aachen and Burtscheid.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Aachen was chosen as the site of several important congresses and peace treaties: the first congress of Aachen (often referred to as the Congress of Aix-la-Chapelle in English) on 2 May 1668, leading to the First Treaty of Aachen in the same year which ended the War of Devolution.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The second congress ended with the second treaty in 1748, ending the War of the Austrian Succession.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] In 1789, there was a constitutional crisis in the Aachen government, and in 1794 Aachen lost its status as a free imperial city.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] In 1629, the Aachen Jewish community was expelled from the city.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] In 1667, six Jews were allowed to return.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Most of the Aachen Jewish community settled in Burtscheid.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] As recently as the late 18th century the Abbess of Burtscheid was still prevented from building a road linking her territory to the neighbouring estates of the duke of Jülich; the city of Aachen deployed its handful of soldiers to chase away road-diggers.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] On 9 February 1801, the Peace of Lunéville removed the ownership of Aachen and the entire "left bank" of the Rhine from Germany (the Holy Roman Empire) and granted it to France.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] In 1815, control of the town was passed to the Kingdom of Prussia through an agreement reached by the Congress of Vienna.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The third congress took place in 1818, to decide the fate of occupied Napoleonic France.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The current territory of Aachen belonged entirely to the Arrondissement d'Aix-la-Chapelle.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] In 1815, after the Second Treaty of Paris, finishing the Napoleonic Wars, the Kingdom of Prussia took over within the new German Confederation.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The city was one of its most socially and politically backward centres until the end of the 19th century.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The Kingdom of Prussia created the "Regierungsbezirk Aachen" (governmental district) and integrated it into the Prussian province Grand Duchy of the Lower Rhine, from 1822 the Rhine Province.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Starting in 1838, the railway from Cologne to Belgium passed through Aachen.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] By "Gesetz betreffend die Vereinigung der Stadtgemeinde Burtscheid mit der Stadtgemeinde Aachen vom 29.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] März 1897 nebst Vertrag" Aachen and Burtscheid merged 1897.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The city suffered extreme overcrowding and deplorable sanitary conditions until 1875, when the medieval fortifications were abandoned as a limit to building and new, better housing was built in the east of the city, where sanitary drainage was easiest.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] In December 1880, the Aachen tramway network was opened, and in 1895 it was electrified.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] In the 19th century and up to the 1930s, the city was important in the production of railway locomotives and carriages, iron, pins, needles, buttons, tobacco, woollen goods, and silk goods.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Aachen was enlarged 1 April 1906 by "Gesetz betreffend die Vereinigung der Gemeinde Forst mit der Stadtgemeinde Aachen vom 31.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] März 1906 nebst Vertrag" by incorporation of Forst.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The Belgium Campaign within World War I started in Aachen.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] After World War I, Aachen was occupied by the Entente until 1930, along with the rest of German territory west of the Rhine.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Aachen was one of the locations involved in the Rhenish Republic.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] On 21 October 1923, an armed mob took over the city hall.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Similar actions took place in Mönchengladbach, Duisburg, and Krefeld.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] During the interwar period, Aachen was assigned some areas of the former district of Eupen.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Also the Western Campaign of World War II started nearby Aachen with the Battle of Maastricht.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Aachen was heavily damaged during World War II.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Blood mentioned more than 120 air strikes on Aachen between 1940 an 1944.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] According to Jörg Friedrich in *The Fire* (2002), two Allied air raids on 11 April and 24 May 1944 "radically destroyed" the city.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The first killed 1,525, including 212 children, and bombed six hospitals.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] During the second, 442 aircraft hit two railway stations, killed 207, and left 15,000 homeless.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The raids destroyed Aachen-Eilendorf and Aachen-Burtscheid.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] In autumn 1944 Aachen and its surroundings were reached by the Western Allied Siegfried Line campaign.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The city and its fortified surroundings were besieged from 12 September to 21 October 1944 by the US 1st Infantry Division with the 3rd Armored Division assisting from the south.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Around 13 October the US 2nd Armored Division, coming from the north, and got as close as Würselen, while the 30th Infantry Division completed the encirclement of Aachen on 16 October 1944.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] With reinforcements from the US 28th Infantry Division the battle continued involving direct assaults through the heavily defended city, which forced the German garrison to surrender on 21 October 1944.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Aachen was the first German city to be captured by the Western Allies, and its residents welcomed the soldiers as liberators.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] What remained of the city was destroyed—in some areas completely—during the fighting, mostly by American artillery fire and demolitions carried out by the Waffen-SS defenders.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Damaged buildings included medieval churches and the Rathaus (city hall), although Aachen Cathedral was largely unscathed.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] 4,000 inhabitants remained in the city; the rest had followed evacuation orders.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Its first Allied-appointed mayor, Franz Oppenhoff, was assassinated by an SS commando unit.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] On 16 May 1815, the Jewish community of the city offered an homage in its synagogue to the Prussian king, Friedrich Wilhelm III.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] In 1862, a large synagogue was built, later called the Old Synagogue.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] On *Kristallnacht* in 1938, the synagogue was destroyed.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] By the onset of World War II in 1939, many Jews had emigrated or were arrested, and only 782 remained in the city.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] At the end of the war in 1945, only 62 Jews lived in the city.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] As of 2003, 1,434 Jews were again living in Aachen.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Subsequent the German surrender finishing the Battle of Aachen 21 October 1944, the Supreme Headquarters Allied Expeditionary Force acted as military government.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Aachen within the northern part of Rhine Province became part of British occupation zone in Germany.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Aachen also belonged to the British zone under Belgian control.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] 46, British Military Government created the "Land Nordrhein/Westfalen", including the "Regierungsbezirk Aachen", 23 August 1946.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] 23 May 1949 Aachen became part of the Federal Republic of Germany.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] With the Aachen Law of 1971, Aachen was merged with Kornelimünster, Brand, Walheim, Laurensberg, Richterich, Haaren, Eilendorf.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] After the abolition of the Aachen governmental district, August 1972, Aachen became part of the Cologne governmental district.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Aachen is located in the middle of the Meuse–Rhine Euroregion, close to the border tripoint of Germany, the Netherlands, and Belgium.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The town of Vaals in the Netherlands lies nearby at about 6 km (4 mi) from Aachen's city centre, while the Dutch city of Heerlen and Eupen, the capital of the German-speaking Community of Belgium, are both located about 20 km (12 mi) from Aachen city centre.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Aachen lies near the head of the open valley of the Wurm (which today flows through the city in canalised form), part of the larger basin of the Meuse, and about 30 km (19 mi) north of the High Fens, which form the northern edge of the Eifel uplands of the Rhenish Massif.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The maximum dimensions of the city's territory are 21.6 km (13+3⁄8 mi) from north to south, and 17.2 km (10+3⁄4 mi) from east to west.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The highest point in Aachen, located in the far southeast of the city, lies at an elevation of 410 m (1,350 ft) above sea level.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The lowest point, in the north, and on the border with the Netherlands, is at 125 m (410 ft).
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] As the westernmost city in Germany (and close to the Low Countries), Aachen and the surrounding area belongs to a temperate climate zone (Cfb), with humid weather, mild winters, and warm summers.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Because of its location north of the Eifel and the High Fens and its subsequent prevailing westerly weather patterns, rainfall in Aachen (on average 805 mm/year) is comparatively higher than, for example, in Bonn (with 669 mm/year).
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Another factor in the local weather forces of Aachen is the occurrence of Foehn winds on the southerly air currents, which results from the city's geographic location on the northern edge of the Eifel.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Because the city is surrounded by hills, it suffers from inversion-related smog.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Some areas of the city have become urban heat islands as a result of poor heat exchange, both because of the area's natural geography and from human activity.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The city's numerous cold air corridors, which are slated to remain as free as possible from new construction, therefore play an important role in the urban climate of Aachen.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The January average is 3.0 °C (37 °F), while the July average is 18.5 °C (65 °F).
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Precipitation is almost evenly spread throughout the year.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] In the 1991–2020 period, the record latest freeze (at 2 m above ground) of spring occurred on 28 April and the record first fall freeze on 13 October.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The geology of Aachen is very structurally heterogeneous.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The oldest occurring rocks in the area surrounding the city originate from the Devonian period and include carboniferous sandstone, greywacke, claystone and limestone.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] These formations are part of the Rhenish Massif, north of the High Fens.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] In the Pennsylvanian subperiod of the Carboniferous geological period, these rock layers were narrowed and folded as a result of the Variscan orogeny.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] After this event, and over the course of the following 200 million years, this area has been continuously flattened.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] During the Cretaceous period, the ocean penetrated the continent from the direction of the North Sea up to the mountainous area near Aachen, bringing with it clay, sand, and chalk deposits.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] While the clay (which was the basis for a major pottery industry in nearby Raeren) is mostly found in the lower areas of Aachen, the hills of the Aachen Forest and the Lousberg were formed from upper Cretaceous sand and chalk deposits.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] More recent sedimentation is mainly located in the north and east of Aachen and was formed through Tertiary and Quaternary river and wind activities.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Along the major thrust fault of the Variscan orogeny, there are over 30 thermal springs in Aachen and Burtscheid.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] At the end of 2009, the foreign-born residents of Aachen made up 13.6 percent of the total population.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] A significant portion of foreign residents are students at the RWTH Aachen University.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Aachen is at the western end of the Benrath line that divides High German to the south from the rest of the West Germanic speech area to the north.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Aachen's local dialect is called *Öcher Platt* and belongs to Ripuarian.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The city is divided into seven administrative districts, or boroughs, each with its own district council, district leader, and district authority.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The councils are elected locally by those who live within the district, and these districts are further subdivided into smaller sections for statistical purposes, with each sub-district named by a two-digit number.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The current mayor of Aachen is Michael Ziemons of the CDU, who was elected in 2025.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The Aachen city council governs the city alongside the mayor.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Aachen Cathedral was erected on the orders of Charlemagne.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Construction began *c.* AD 796, and it was, on completion *c.* 798, the largest cathedral north of the Alps.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] It was modelled after the Basilica of San Vitale, in Ravenna, Italy, and was built by Odo of Metz.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Charlemagne also desired for the chapel to compete with the Lateran Palace, both in quality and authority.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] It was originally built in the Carolingian style, including marble covered walls, and mosaic inlay on the dome.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] On his death, Charlemagne's remains were interred in the cathedral and can be seen there to this day.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The cathedral was extended several times in later ages, turning it into a curious and unique mixture of building styles.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The throne and gallery portion date from the Ottonian, with portions of the original opus sectile floor still visible.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The 13th century saw gables being added to the roof, and after the fire of 1656, the dome was rebuilt.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Finally, a choir was added around the start of the 15th century.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] After Frederick Barbarossa canonised Charlemagne in 1165 the chapel became a destination for pilgrims.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] For 600 years, from 936 to 1531, Aachen Cathedral was the church of coronation for 30 German kings and 12 queens.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The church built by Charlemagne is still the main attraction of the city.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] In addition to holding the remains of its founder, it became the burial place of his successor Otto III.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] In the upper chamber of the gallery, Charlemagne's marble throne is housed.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Aachen Cathedral has been designated as a UNESCO World Heritage Site.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Most of the marble and columns used in the construction of the cathedral were brought from Rome and Ravenna, including the sarcophagus in which Charlemagne was eventually laid to rest.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] A bronze bear from Gaul was placed inside, along with an equestrian statue from Ravenna, believed to be Theodric, in contrast to a wolf and a statue of Marcus Aurelius in the Capitoline.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Bronze pieces such as the doors and railings, some of which have survived to present day, were cast in a local foundry.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Finally, there is uncertainty surrounding the bronze pine cone in the chapel, and where it was created.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Wherever it was made, it was also a parallel to a piece in Rome, this in Old St.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Aachen Cathedral Treasury has housed, throughout its history, a collection of liturgical objects.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The origin of this church treasure is in dispute as some say Charlemagne himself endowed his chapel with the original collection, while the rest were collected over time.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Others say all of the objects were collected over time, from such places as Jerusalem and Constantinople.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The location of this treasury has moved over time and was unknown until the 15th century when it was located in the Matthiaskapelle (St.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Matthew's Chapel) until 1873, when it was moved to the Karlskapelle (Charles' Chapel).
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] From there it was moved to the Hungarian Chapel in 1881 and in 1931 to its present location next to the Allerseelenkapelle (Poor Souls' Chapel).
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Only six of the original Carolingian objects have remained, and of those only three are left in Aachen: the Aachen Gospels, a diptych of Christ, and an early Byzantine silk.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The Coronation Gospels and a reliquary burse of St.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Stephen were moved to Vienna in 1798 and the Talisman of Charlemagne was given as a gift in 1804 to Josephine Bonaparte and subsequently to Rheims Cathedral.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] 210 documented pieces have been added to the treasury since its inception, typically to receive in return legitimisation of linkage to the heritage of Charlemagne.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The Lothar Cross, the Gospels of Otto III and multiple additional Byzantine silks were donated by Otto III.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Part of the Pala d'Oro and a covering for the Aachen Gospels were made of gold donated by Henry II.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Frederick Barbarossa donated the candelabrum that adorns the dome and also once "crowned" the Shrine of Charlemagne, which was placed underneath in 1215.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Charles IV donated a pair of reliquaries.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Louis XI gave, in 1475, the crown of Margaret of York, and, in 1481, another arm reliquary of Charlemagne.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Maximilian I and Charles V both gave numerous works of art by Hans von Reutlingen.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Continuing the tradition, objects continued to be donated until the present, each indicative of the period of its gifting, with the last documented gift being a chalice from 1960 made by Ewald Mataré.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The Aachen Rathaus, (English: Aachen City Hall or Aachen Town Hall) dated from 1330, lies between two central squares, the *Markt* (marketplace) and the *Katschhof* (between city hall and cathedral).
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The coronation hall is on the first floor of the building.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Inside one can find five frescoes by the Aachen artist Alfred Rethel which show legendary scenes from the life of Charlemagne, as well as Charlemagne's signature.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Also, precious replicas of the Imperial Regalia are kept here.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Since 2009, the city hall has been a station on the *Route Charlemagne*, a tour programme by which historical sights of Aachen are presented to visitors.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] At the city hall, a museum exhibition explains the history and art of the building and gives a sense of the historical coronation banquets that took place there.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] A portrait of Napoleon from 1807 by Louis-André-Gabriel Bouchet and one of his wife Joséphine from 1805 by Robert Lefèvre are viewable as part of the tour.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] As before, the city hall is the seat of the mayor of Aachen and of the city council, and annually the Charlemagne Prize is awarded there.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The *Grashaus*, a late medieval house at the *Fischmarkt*, is one of the oldest non-religious buildings in central Aachen.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] It hosted the city archive, and before that, the Grashaus was the city hall until the present building took over this function.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The *Elisenbrunnen* is one of the most famous sights of Aachen.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] It is a neo-classical hall covering one of the city's famous fountains.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] It is just a minute away from the cathedral.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Just a few steps in a south-easterly direction lies the 19th-century theatre.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Also of note are two remaining city gates, the *Ponttor* (Pont gate), 800 metres (1⁄2 mile) northwest of the cathedral, and the *Marschiertor* (marching gate), close to the central railway station.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] There are also a few parts of both medieval city walls left, most of them integrated into more recent buildings, but some others still visible.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] There are even five towers left, some of which are used for housing.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Michael's Church, Aachen was built as a church of the Aachen Jesuit Collegium in 1628.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] It is attributed to the Rhine mannerism, and a sample of a local Renaissance architecture.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The rich façade remained unfinished until 1891, when the architect Peter Friedrich Peters added to it.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The church is a Greek Orthodox church today, but the building is used also for concerts because of its good acoustics.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The synagogue in Aachen, which was destroyed on the Night of Broken Glass (Kristallnacht), 9 November 1938, was reinaugurated on 18 May 1995.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] One of the contributors to the reconstructions of the synagogue was Jürgen Linden, the Lord Mayor of Aachen from 1989 to 2009.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] There are numerous other notable churches and monasteries, a few remarkable 17th- and 18th-century buildings in the particular Baroque style typical of the region, a synagogue, a collection of statues and monuments, park areas, cemeteries, among others.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Among the museums in the town are the Suermondt-Ludwig Museum, which has a fine sculpture collection and the Aachen Museum of the International Press, which is dedicated to newspapers from the 16th century to the present.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] The area's industrial history is reflected in dozens of 19th- and early 20th-century manufacturing sites in the city.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Aachen is the administrative centre for the coal-mining industries in neighbouring places to the northeast.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Products manufactured in Aachen include electrical goods, fine woolen textiles, foodstuffs (chocolate and candy), glass, machinery, rubber products, furniture, metal products.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Also in and around Aachen chemicals, plastics, cosmetics, and needles and pins are produced.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Though once a major player in Aachen's economy, today glassware and textile production make up only 10% of total manufacturing jobs in the city.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] There have been a number of spin-offs from the university's IT technology department.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] In June 2010, Achim Kampker, together with Günther Schuh, founded a small company to develop electric powered light utility vehicles; in August 2014, it was renamed StreetScooter GmbH.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] This started as a privately organised research initiative at the RWTH Aachen University, before becoming the independent company in Aachen.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] Kampker was also the founder and chairman of the European Network for Affordable and Sustainable Electromobility.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] In May 2014, the company announced that the city of Aachen, the city council Aachen and the savings bank Aachen had ordered electric vehicles from the company.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] In late 2014, approximately 70 employees were manufacturing 200 vehicles annually in the premises of the Waggonfabrik Talbot, the former Talbot/Bombardier plant in Aachen.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] In December 2014 DHL Group purchased the StreetScooter company from Günther, operating it as a wholly owned subsidiary.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] In 2015, Günther founded a new electric vehicle company, e.GO Mobile, which started producing the e.GO Life electric passenger car and other vehicles in April 2019.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] By April 2016, StreetScooter announced that it would produce 2000 of its electric vans, branded the Work, in Aachen by the end of the year, and would be scaling up to manufacture approximately 10,000 Works annually, starting in 2017, also in Aachen.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p01] At the time, this target would make it the largest electric light utility vehicle manufacturer in Europe, surpassing Renault's smaller Kangoo Z.E.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] RWTH Aachen University, established as Polytechnicum in 1870, is one of Germany's Universities of Excellence with strong emphasis on technological research, especially for electrical and mechanical engineering, computer sciences, physics, and chemistry.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] The university clinic attached to the RWTH, the Klinikum Aachen, is the biggest single-building hospital in Europe.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] Over time, a host of software and computer industries have developed around the university.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] It also maintains a botanical garden (the Botanischer Garten Aachen).
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] FH Aachen, Aachen University of Applied Sciences (AcUAS) was founded in 1971.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] The AcUAS offers a classic engineering education in professions such as mechatronics, construction engineering, mechanical engineering or electrical engineering.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] German and international students are educated in more than 20 international or foreign-oriented programmes and can acquire German as well as international degrees (Bachelor/Master) or *Doppelabschlüsse* (double degrees).
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] Foreign students account for more than 21% of the student body.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] The Katholische Hochschule Nordrhein-Westfalen – Abteilung Aachen (Catholic University of Applied Sciences Northrhine-Westphalia – Aachen department) offers its some 750 students a variety of degree programmes: social work, childhood education, nursing, and co-operative management.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] It also has the only programme of study in Germany especially designed for mothers.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] The Hochschule für Musik und Tanz Köln (Cologne University of Music) is one of the world's foremost performing arts schools and one of the largest music institutions for higher education in Europe with one of its three campuses in Aachen.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] The Aachen campus substantially contributes to the Opera/Musical Theatre master's programme by collaborating with the Theater Aachen and the recently established musical theatre chair through the Rheinische Opernakademie.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] The German Army's technical school *(Ausbildungszentrum Technik Landsysteme)* is located in Aachen.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] The annual CHIO (short for the French term *Concours Hippique International Officiel*) is the biggest equestrian meeting of the world and among horsemen is considered to be as prestigious for equitation as the tournament of Wimbledon for tennis.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] Aachen hosted the 2006 FEI World Equestrian Games.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] The local football team Alemannia Aachen had a short run in Germany's first division, after its promotion in 2006.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] However, the team could not sustain its status and is now back in the third division.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] The stadium "Tivoli", opened in 1928, served as the venue for the team's home games and was well known for its incomparable atmosphere throughout the whole of the second division.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] Before the old stadium's demolition in 2011, it was used by amateurs, whilst the Bundesliga Club held its games in the new stadium "Neuer Tivoli" – meaning New Tivoli—a couple of metres down the road.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] The building work for the stadium which has a capacity of 32,960, began in May 2008 and was completed by the beginning of 2009.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] The Ladies in Black women's volleyball team (part of the "PTSV Aachen" sports club since 2013) has played in the first German volleyball league (DVL) since 2008.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] In June 2022, the local basketball club BG Aachen e.V. was promoted to the 1st regional league.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] Aachen's railway station, the Hauptbahnhof (Central Station), was constructed in 1841 for the Cologne–Aachen railway line.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] In 1905, it was moved closer to the city centre.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] It serves main lines to Cologne, Mönchengladbach and Liège as well as branch lines to Heerlen, Alsdorf, Stolberg and Eschweiler.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] ICE high speed trains from Brussels via Cologne to Frankfurt am Main and Eurostar trains from Paris to Cologne also stop at Aachen Central Station.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] Four RE lines and two RB lines connect Aachen with the Ruhrgebiet, Mönchengladbach, Spa (Belgium), Düsseldorf and the Siegerland.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] The *Euregiobahn*, a regional railway system, reaches several minor cities in the Aachen region.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] There are four smaller stations in Aachen: *Aachen West*, *Aachen Schanz*, *Aachen-Rothe Erde* and *Eilendorf*.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] Aachen West has gained in importance with the expansion of RWTH Aachen University.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] There are two stations for intercity bus services in Aachen: Aachen West station, in the north-west of the city, and Aachen Wilmersdorfer Straße, in the north-east.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] The first horse tram line in Aachen opened in December 1880.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] After electrification in 1895, it attained a maximum length of 213.5 kilometres (132+5⁄8 miles) in 1915, thus becoming the fourth-longest tram network in Germany.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] Many tram lines extended to the surrounding towns of Herzogenrath, Stolberg, Alsdorf as well as the Belgian and Dutch communes of Vaals, Kelmis (then *Altenberg*) and Eupen.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] The Aachen tram system was linked with the Belgian national interurban tram system.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] Like many tram systems in Western Europe, the Aachen tram suffered from poorly maintained infrastructure and was so deemed unnecessary and disrupting for car drivers by local politics.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] On 28 September 1974, the last line 15 (Vaals–Brand) operated for one last day and was then replaced by buses.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] A proposal to reinstate a tram/light rail system under the name *Campusbahn* was dropped after a referendum.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] Today, the ASEAG (*Aachener Straßenbahn und Energieversorgungs-AG*, literally "Aachen Tram and Power Supply Company") operates a 1,240.8-kilometre-long (771 mi) bus network with 68 bus routes.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] Because of the location at the border, many bus routes extend to Belgium and the Netherlands.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] Lines 14 to Eupen, Belgium and 44 to Heerlen, Netherlands are jointly operated with Transport en Commun and Veolia Transport Nederland, respectively.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] ASEAG is one of the main participants in the Aachener Verkehrsverbund (AVV), a tariff association in the region.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] Along with ASEAG, city bus routes of Aachen are served by private contractors such as Sadar, Taeter, Schlömer, or DB Regio Bus.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] Line 350, which runs from Maastricht, also enters Aachen.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] Aachen is connected to the Autobahn A4 (west-east), A44 (north-south) and A544 (a smaller motorway from the A4 to the *Europaplatz* near the city centre).
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] There are plans to eliminate traffic jams at the Aachen road interchange.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] Maastricht Aachen Airport (IATA: **MST**, ICAO: **EHBK**) is the main airport of Aachen and Maastricht.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] It is located around 15 nautical miles (28 kilometres; 17 miles) northwest of Aachen.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] There is a shuttle-service between Aachen and the airport.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] However, the airport only offers limited European destinations.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] The nearest major international airports are Cologne Bonn Airport, located 88 km (55 mi) east and Düsseldorf Airport, located 97.1 km (60 mi) northeast of Aachen.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] Recreational aviation is served by the (formerly military) Aachen Merzbrück Airfield.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] Since 1950, a committee of Aachen citizens annually awards the Charlemagne Prize (German: *Karlspreis*) to personalities of outstanding service to the unification of Europe.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] It is traditionally awarded on Ascension Day at the City Hall.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] In 2016, the Charlemagne Award was awarded to Pope Francis.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] In 2004, Pope John Paul II's efforts to unite Europe were honoured with an "Extraordinary Charlemagne Medal", which was awarded for the only time ever.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] Aix is the destination in Robert Browning's poem "How They Brought the Good News from Ghent to Aix", which was published in *Dramatic Romances and Lyrics*, 1845.
[src:advocaat/aachen-p02] The poem is a first-person narrative told, in breathless galloping meter, by one of three riders; an urgent midnight errand to deliver "the news which alone could save Aix from her fate".
[src:advocaat/aachener-zeitung] The AZ was founded in 1946 as ***Aachener Volkszeitung*** (AVZ) by Jakob Schmitz, Josef Hofmann, Albert Maas and Johannes Ernst, first printed on 22 February 1946.
[src:advocaat/aachener-zeitung] It was the first free paper published by Germans after World War II.
[src:advocaat/aachener-zeitung] The paper was renamed *Aachener Zeitung* on 6 March 1996.
[src:advocaat/aachener-zeitung] The paper was printed initially only two or three times a week, but daily every working day from 1 September 1949; it is sold mainly by subscription and the circulation is about 112,000 copies.
[src:advocaat/aachener-zeitung] The paper supplies news from around the world, but with a focus on the region, its politics, economy, culture, sports and weather, for readers in Aachen, Eschweiler, Geilenkirchen and Jülich.
[src:advocaat/aachener-zeitung] Bernd Mathieu is the current editor-in-chief, of the Aachener Zeitung from 1995 and of the Aachener Nachrichten from 2003.
[src:advocaat/aachener-zeitung] The concept of two newspapers in one *Redaktion* was then new for Germany.
[src:advocaat/aachener-zeitung] Mathieu is a lecturer at the Aachen University of Applied Sciences for *Digital Business* in media and communications studies.
[src:advocaat/aachener-zeitung] He is a member of the jury of the journalism prize Theodor Wolff Prize.
[src:advocaat/aachener-zeitung] Mathieu initiated online news service, namely a digital daily evening news "AmAbend" with photo galleries and videos, provided from 7 pm, in addition to the printed papers which include weekly specials on Wednesdays and Sundays.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Absinthe was created in the canton of Neuchâtel in Switzerland in the late 18th century by the French physician Pierre Ordinaire.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] It rose to great popularity as an alcoholic drink in late 19th- and early 20th-century France, particularly among Parisian artists and writers.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The consumption of absinthe was opposed by social conservatives and prohibitionists, partly due to its association with bohemian culture.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] From Europe and the Americas, notable absinthe drinkers included Ernest Hemingway, James Joyce, Lewis Carroll, Charles Baudelaire, Paul Verlaine, Arthur Rimbaud, and Henri de Toulouse-Lautrec.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Absinthe has often been portrayed as a dangerously addictive psychoactive drug and hallucinogen, which gave birth to the term *absinthism*.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The chemical compound thujone, which is present in the spirit in trace amounts, was blamed for its alleged harmful effects.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] By 1915, absinthe had been banned in the United States and much of Europe, including France, the Netherlands, Belgium, Switzerland, and Austria-Hungary, though it has not been demonstrated to be any more dangerous than ordinary spirits.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Recent studies have shown that absinthe's psychoactive properties, apart from those attributable to its alcohol content, have been exaggerated.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Absinthe's revival began in the 1990s, following the adoption of modern European Union food and beverage laws that removed long-standing barriers to its production and sale.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] By the early 21st century, nearly 200 brands of absinthe were being produced in a dozen countries, most notably in France, Switzerland, Austria, Germany, the Netherlands, Spain, and the Czech Republic.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The French word *absinthe* can refer either to the alcoholic beverage, or less commonly, to the actual wormwood plant.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Absinthe is derived from the Latin *absinthium*, which in turn comes from the Greek ἀψίνθιον *apsínthion* 'wormwood'.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Some argue that the word means "undrinkable" in Greek, but it may instead be linked to the Persian root, in Persian called *spand* or *aspand* or the variant *esfand*, which meant *Peganum harmala*, also called Syrian rue in English, although it is not a variety of rue, another famously bitter herb.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] That *Artemisia absinthium* was commonly burned as a protective offering may suggest that its origins lie in the reconstructed Proto-Indo-European language root **spend*, meaning "to perform a ritual" or "make an offering".
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Whether the word was a borrowing from Persian into Greek, or from a common ancestor of both, is unclear.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Alternatively, the Greek word may originate in a pre-Greek substrate word, marked by the non-Indo-European consonant complex -νθ *-nth*.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Alternative spellings for absinthe include *absinth*, *absynthe*, and *absenta*.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] *Absinth* (without the final *e*) is a spelling variant most commonly applied to absinthes produced in central and eastern Europe, and is specifically associated with Bohemian-style absinthes.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The precise origin of absinthe is unclear.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The medical use of wormwood dates back to ancient Egypt and is mentioned in the Ebers Papyrus from around 1550 BC.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Wormwood extracts and wine-soaked wormwood leaves were used as remedies by the ancient Greeks.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Moreover, some evidence exists of a wormwood-flavoured wine in ancient Greece called *absinthites oinos*.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Lucretius' *De Rerum Natura* (I, 936–950) says that a drink containing wormwood was given as medicine to children in a cup with honey on the brim to make it drinkable.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The first evidence of absinthe, in the sense of a distilled spirit containing green anise and fennel, dates to the 18th century.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] According to popular legend, it began as an all-purpose patent remedy created by Dr.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Pierre Ordinaire, a French doctor living in Couvet, Switzerland, around 1792 (the exact date varies by account).
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Ordinaire's recipe was passed on to the Henriod sisters of Couvet, who sold it as a medicinal elixir.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] By other accounts, the Henriod sisters may have been making the elixir before Ordinaire's arrival.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] In either case, a certain Major Dubied acquired the formula from the sisters in 1797 and opened the first absinthe distillery named Dubied Père et Fils in Couvet with his son Marcellin and son-in-law Henry-Louis Pernod.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] In 1805, they built a second distillery in Pontarlier, France, under the company name Maison Pernod Fils.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Pernod Fils remained one of the most popular brands of absinthe until the drink was banned in France in 1914.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Absinthe's popularity grew steadily through the 1840s, when it was given to French troops in Algeria as a malaria preventive, and the troops brought home their taste for it.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Absinthe became so popular in bars, bistros, cafés, and cabarets by the 1860s that the hour of 5 pm was called *l'heure verte* 'the green hour'.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] It was favoured by all social classes, from the wealthy bourgeoisie to poor artists and ordinary working-class people.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] By the 1880s, mass production had caused the price to drop sharply, and the French were drinking 36 million litres (9,500,000 US gal) per year by 1910.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Absinthe was exported widely from France and Switzerland and attained some degree of popularity in other countries, including Spain, the United Kingdom, the United States, and the Czech Republic.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] It was never banned in Spain or Portugal, and its production and consumption have never ceased.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] It gained a temporary popularity spike during the early 20th century, corresponding with the Art Nouveau and Modernism aesthetic movements.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] New Orleans has a cultural association with absinthe and is credited as the birthplace of the Sazerac, perhaps the earliest absinthe cocktail.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The Old Absinthe House bar on Bourbon Street began selling absinthe in the first half of the 19th century.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Its Catalan lease-holder, Cayetano Ferrer, named it the Absinthe Room in 1874 due to the drink's popularity, which was served in the Parisian style.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] It was frequented by Mark Twain, Oscar Wilde, Franklin Delano Roosevelt, Aleister Crowley, and Frank Sinatra.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Absinthe became associated with violent crimes and social disorder, and one modern writer claims that this trend was spurred by fabricated claims and smear campaigns, which he claims were orchestrated by the temperance movement and the wine industry.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Edgar Degas's 1876 painting **The Absinthe Drinker** or **Glass of Absinthe** (**L'Absinthe**) can be seen at the Musée d'Orsay epitomising the popular view of absinthe addicts as sodden and benumbed, and Émile Zola described its effects in his novel *L'Assommoir*.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] In 1905, Swiss farmer Jean Lanfray murdered his wife and two children and then attempted to kill himself after drinking absinthe.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Lanfray had drunk a lot of wine and brandy before the killings, but that was overlooked or ignored, and blame for the murders was placed solely on his consumption of two glasses of absinthe.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The Lanfray murders were the tipping point in this hotly debated topic, and a subsequent petition collected more than 82,000 signatures to ban it in Switzerland.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] It was approved by voters, and the prohibition of absinthe was written into the Swiss constitution.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] In 1906, Belgium and Brazil banned the sale and distribution of absinthe although these were not the first countries to take such action.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] It had been banned as early as 1898 in the colony of the Congo Free State.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The Netherlands banned it in 1909, Switzerland in 1910, the United States in 1912, and France in 1914.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The prohibition of absinthe in France eventually led to the popularity of pastis, and to a lesser extent, ouzo, and other anise-flavoured spirits that do not contain wormwood.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Following the conclusion of the First World War, production of the Pernod Fils brand was resumed at the Banus distillery in Catalonia, Spain (where absinthe was still legal), but gradually declining sales saw the cessation of production in the 1960s.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] In Switzerland, the ban served only to drive the production of absinthe underground.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Clandestine home distillers produced colourless absinthe (*la Bleue*), which was easier to conceal from the authorities.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Many countries never banned absinthe, notably the United Kingdom, where it had never been as popular as in continental Europe.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] British importer BBH Spirits began to import Hill's Absinth from the Czech Republic in the 1990s, as the UK had never formally banned it, and this sparked a modern resurgence in its popularity.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] It began to reappear during a revival in the 1990s in countries where it was never banned.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Forms of absinthe available during that time consisted almost exclusively of Czech, Spanish, and Portuguese brands that were of recent origin, typically consisting of Bohemian-style products.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Connoisseurs considered these of inferior quality and not representative of the 19th-century spirit.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] In 2000, La Fée Absinthe became the first commercial absinthe distilled and bottled in France since the 1914 ban, but it is now one of dozens of brands that are produced and sold within France.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] In the Netherlands, the restrictions were challenged by Amsterdam wine seller Menno Boorsma in July 2004, thus confirming the legality of absinthe once again.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Similarly, Belgium lifted its long-standing ban on 1 January 2005 citing a conflict with the adopted food and beverage regulations of the single European Market.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] In Switzerland, the constitutional ban was repealed in 2000 during an overhaul of the national constitution although the prohibition was written into ordinary law instead.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] That law was later repealed, and absinthe was made legal on March 1, 2005.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The drink was never officially banned in Spain although it began to fall out of favour in the 1940s and almost vanished into obscurity.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Catalonia has seen a significant resurgence since 2007 when one producer established operations there.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Absinthe has never been illegal to import or manufacture in Australia although importation requires a permit under the Customs (Prohibited Imports) Regulation 1956 due to a restriction on importing any product containing oil of wormwood.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] In 2000, an amendment made all wormwood species prohibited herbs for food purposes under Food Standard 1.4.4.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Prohibited and Restricted Plants and Fungi.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] However, this amendment was found inconsistent with other parts of the pre-existing Food Code, and it was withdrawn in 2002 during the transition between the two codes, thereby continuing to allow absinthe manufacture and importation through the existing permit-based system.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] These events were erroneously reported by the media as it having been reclassified from a *prohibited* product to a *restricted* product.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] In 2007, the French brand Lucid became the first genuine absinthe to receive a Certificate of Label Approval for import into the United States since 1912, following independent efforts by representatives from Lucid and Kübler to overturn the long-standing U.S. ban.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] George Spirits of Alameda, California became the first brand of American-made absinthe produced in the United States since the ban.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Since that time, other micro-distilleries have started producing small batches in the United States.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The French Absinthe Ban of 1915 was repealed in May 2011 following petitions by the *Fédération Française des Spiritueux*, which represents French distillers, and the French Senate voted to repeal the prohibition in April 2011.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] In Switzerland, the village of Môtiers, Val-de-Travers, near Neuchâtel, became the focal point of production and promotion of the liquor after a ban of nearly 100 years was lifted.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The national *Maison de l'Absinthe* (House of Absinthe), with its attached museum, is located in the former courthouse where absinthe distillers were formerly prosecuted.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The 21st century has seen new types of absinthe, including various frozen preparations, that have become increasingly popular.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Most countries have no legal definition for absinthe, whereas the method of production and content of spirits such as whisky, brandy, and gin are globally defined and regulated.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Therefore, producers are at liberty to label a product as "absinthe" or "absinth" without regard to any specific legal definition or quality standards.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Producers of legitimate absinthes employ one of two historically defined processes to create the finished spirit – distillation or cold mixing.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] In the sole country (Switzerland) that does possess a legal definition of absinthe, distillation is the only permitted method of production.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Distilled absinthe employs a method of production similar to that of high-quality gin.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Botanicals are initially macerated in distilled base alcohol before being redistilled to exclude bitter principles, and impart the desired complexity and texture to the spirit.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The distillation of absinthe first yields a colourless distillate that leaves the alembic at around 72% ABV.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The distillate may be reduced and bottled clear, to produce a *Blanche* or *la Bleue* absinthe, or it may be coloured to create a *verte* using natural or artificial colouring.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Traditional absinthes obtain their green color strictly from the chlorophyll of whole herbs, which is extracted from the plants during the secondary maceration.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] This step involves steeping plants such as petite wormwood, hyssop, and melissa (among other herbs) in the distillate.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Chlorophyll from these herbs is extracted, giving the drink its famous green color.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] This step also provides a herbal complexity that is typical of high-quality absinthe.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The natural coloring process is critical for absinthe ageing since the chlorophyll remains chemically active.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The chlorophyll serves a similar role in absinthe as tannins do in wine or brown liquors.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] After the coloring process, the resulting product is diluted with water to the desired alcohol percentage.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The flavor of absinthe is said to improve materially with storage, and many distilleries, before the ban, aged their absinthe in settling tanks before bottling.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Many modern absinthes are produced using a cold-mix process.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] This inexpensive method of production does not involve distillation, and is regarded as inferior for the same reasons that give cause for cheaply compounded gin to be legally differentiated from distilled gin.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The cold mixing process involves the simple blending of flavouring essences and artificial colouring in commercial alcohol, in similar fashion to most flavoured vodkas and inexpensive liqueurs and cordials.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Some modern cold-mixed absinthes have been bottled at strengths approaching 90% ABV.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Others are presented simply as a bottle of plain alcohol with a small amount of powdered herbs suspended within it.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The lack of a formal legal definition in most countries to regulate the production and quality of absinthe has enabled cheaply made products to be falsely presented as traditional in production and composition.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] In Switzerland, the only country with a formal legal definition of absinthe, any absinthe product not obtained by maceration and distillation or coloured artificially cannot be sold as absinthe.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Absinthe is traditionally prepared from a distillation of neutral alcohol, various herbs, spices, and water.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Traditional absinthes were redistilled from a white grape spirit (or *eau de vie*), while lesser absinthes were more commonly made from alcohol from grains, beets, or potatoes.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The principal botanicals are grande wormwood, green anise, and florence fennel, which are often called "the holy trinity".
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Many other herbs may be used as well, such as petite wormwood (*Artemisia pontica* or Roman wormwood), hyssop, melissa, star anise, angelica, peppermint, coriander, and veronica.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] One early recipe was included in 1864's *The English and Australian Cookery Book*.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] It directed the maker to "Take of the tops of wormwood, four pounds; root of angelica, calamus aromaticus, aniseed, leaves of dittany, of each one ounce; alcohol, four gallons.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Macerate these substances during eight days, add a little water, and distil by a gentle fire, until two gallons are obtained.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Adding to absinthe's negative reputation in the late 19th and early 20th centuries, unscrupulous makers of the drink omitted the traditional colouring phase of production in favour of adding toxic copper salts to artificially induce a green tint.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] This practice may be responsible for some of the alleged toxicity historically associated with this beverage.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Many modern-day producers resort to other shortcuts, including the use of artificial food coloring to create the green color.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Additionally, at least some cheap absinthes produced before the ban were reportedly adulterated with poisonous antimony trichloride, reputed to enhance the louching effect.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Absinthe may also be naturally coloured pink or red using rose or hibiscus flowers.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] This was referred to as a *rose* (pink) or *rouge* (red) absinthe.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Only one historical brand of rose absinthe has been documented.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Absinthe was historically bottled at 45–74% ABV.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Some modern Franco–Suisse absinthes are bottled at up to 83% ABV, while some modern, cold-mixed bohemian-style absinthes are bottled at up to 89.9% ABV.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The modern-day interest in absinthe has spawned a rash of absinthe kits from sellers claiming they produce homemade absinthe.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Kits often call for soaking herbs in vodka or alcohol or adding a liquid concentrate to vodka or alcohol to create an ersatz absinthe.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Such practices usually yield a harsh substance that bears little resemblance to the genuine article and is considered inauthentic by any practical standard.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Some concoctions may even be dangerous, especially if they call for a potentially poisonous inclusion of herbs, oils, or extracts.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] In at least one documented case, a person suffered acute kidney injury after drinking 10 ml of pure wormwood oil.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] In baking and in preparing the classic New Orleans-style Sazerac cocktail, anise-flavored liqueurs and pastis have often been used as a substitute if absinthe is unavailable.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The traditional French preparation involves placing a sugar cube on top of a specially designed slotted spoon and placing the spoon on a glass filled with a measure of absinthe.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Iced water is poured or dripped over the sugar cube to mix the water into the absinthe.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The final preparation contains 1 part absinthe and 3–5 parts water.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] As water dilutes the spirit, those components with poor water solubility (mainly those from anise, fennel, and star anise) come out of solution and cloud the drink.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The resulting milky opalescence is called the *louche* (/luʃ/, French: 'opaque' or 'shady').
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The release of these dissolved essences coincides with a perfuming of herbal aromas and flavours that "blossom" or "bloom", and brings out subtleties that are otherwise muted within the neat spirit.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] This reflects what is perhaps the oldest and purest method of preparation, and is often referred to as the *French method*.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The *Bohemian method* is a recent invention that involves fire, and was not performed during absinthe's peak of popularity in the Belle Époque.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Like the French method, a sugar cube is placed on a slotted spoon over a glass containing one shot of absinthe.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The sugar is soaked in alcohol (usually more absinthe), and then set ablaze.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The flaming sugar cube is then dropped into the glass, thus igniting the absinthe.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Finally, a shot glass of water is added to douse the flames.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] This method tends to produce a stronger drink than the French method.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] A variant of the Bohemian method involves allowing the fire to extinguish on its own.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] This variant is sometimes referred to as "cooking the absinthe" or "the flaming green fairy".
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The origin of this burning ritual may borrow from a coffee and brandy drink that was served at Café Brûlot, in which a sugar cube soaked in brandy was set aflame.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Most experienced absintheurs do not recommend the Bohemian Method and consider it a modern gimmick, as it can destroy the absinthe flavour and present a fire hazard due to the unusually high alcohol content present in absinthe.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] In 19th-century Parisian cafés, upon receiving an order for absinthe, a waiter would present the patron with a dose of absinthe in a suitable glass, sugar, absinthe spoon, and a carafe of iced water.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] It was up to the patron to prepare the drink, as the inclusion or omission of sugar was strictly an individual preference, as was the amount of water used.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] As the popularity of the drink increased, additional accoutrements of preparation appeared, including the absinthe fountain, which was effectively a large jar of iced water with spigots, mounted on a lamp base.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] This lets drinkers prepare several drinks at once – and with a hands-free drip, patrons could socialise while louching a glass.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Although many bars served absinthe in standard glassware, several glasses were specifically designed for the French absinthe preparation ritual.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Absinthe glasses were typically fashioned with a dose line, bulge, or bubble in the lower portion denoting how much absinthe should be poured.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] One "dose" of absinthe ranged anywhere around 2–2.5 fluid ounces (60–75 ml).
[src:advocaat/absinthe] In addition to being prepared with sugar and water, absinthe emerged as a popular cocktail ingredient in both the United Kingdom and the United States.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] By 1930, dozens of fancy cocktails that called for absinthe had been published in numerous credible bartender guides.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] One of the most famous of these libations is Ernest Hemingway's "Death in the Afternoon" cocktail, a tongue-in-cheek concoction that contributed to a 1935 collection of celebrity recipes.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The directions are: "Pour one jigger absinthe into a Champagne glass.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Add iced Champagne until it attains the proper opalescent milkiness.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Most categorical alcoholic beverages have regulations governing their classification and labelling, while those governing absinthe have always been conspicuously lacking.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] According to popular treatises from the 19th century, absinthe could be loosely categorised into several grades (*ordinaire*, *demi-fine*, *fine*, and *Suisse* – the latter does not denote origin), in order of increasing alcoholic strength and quality.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Many contemporary absinthe critics simply classify absinthe as *distilled* or *mixed*, according to its production method.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] And while the former is generally considered far superior in quality to the latter, an absinthe's simple claim of being 'distilled' makes no guarantee as to the quality of its base ingredients or the skill of its maker.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Absinthe that is artificially coloured or clear is aesthetically stable and can be bottled in clear glass.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] If naturally colored absinthe is exposed to light or air for a prolonged period, the chlorophyll gradually becomes oxidized, which has the effect of gradually changing the color from green to yellow green, and eventually to brown.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The colour of absinthe that has completed this transition was historically referred to as *feuille morte* ("dead leaf").
[src:advocaat/absinthe] In the pre-ban era, this natural phenomenon was favourably viewed, for it confirmed the product in question was coloured naturally, and not artificially with potentially toxic chemicals.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Predictably, vintage absinthes often emerge from sealed bottles as distinctly amber in tint due to decades of slow oxidation.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Though this colour change presents no adverse impact to the flavour of absinthe, it is generally desired to preserve the original colour, which requires that naturally coloured absinthe be bottled in dark, light-resistant bottles.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Absinthe intended for decades of storage should be kept in a cool (room temperature), dry place, away from light and heat.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Absinthe should not be stored in the refrigerator or freezer, as the anethole may polymerise inside the bottle, creating an irreversible precipitate, and adversely impacting the original flavour.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Absinthe has been frequently described in modern times as being hallucinogenic, a claim refuted by modern science.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The belief that absinthe induces hallucinogenic effects is rooted, at least partly, in the findings of 19th-century French psychiatrist Valentin Magnan, who carried out ten years of experiments with wormwood oil.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] In the course of this research, he studied 250 cases of alcoholism and concluded that those who abused absinthe were worse off than those who abused other alcoholic drinks, experiencing rapid-onset hallucinations.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Such accounts by opponents of absinthe (like Magnan) were cheerfully embraced by famous absinthe drinkers, many of whom were bohemian artists or writers.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Two famous artists who helped popularise the notion that absinthe had powerful psychoactive properties were Toulouse-Lautrec and Vincent van Gogh.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] In one of the best-known written accounts of absinthe drinking, an inebriated Oscar Wilde described a phantom sensation of having tulips brush against his legs after leaving a bar at closing time.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Notions of absinthe's alleged hallucinogenic properties were again fuelled in the 1970s when a scientific paper suggested that thujone's structural similarity to tetrahydrocannabinol (THC), the active chemical in cannabis, presented the possibility of THC receptor affinity.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Counterevidence to this was published in 1999.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The debate over whether absinthe produces effects on the human mind in addition to those of alcohol has not been resolved conclusively.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The effects of absinthe have been described by some as mind-opening.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The most commonly reported experience is a "clear-headed" feeling of inebriation – a form of "lucid drunkenness".
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Chemist, historian, and absinthe distiller Ted Breaux has claimed that the alleged secondary effects of absinthe may be because some of the herbal compounds in the drink act as stimulants, while others act as sedatives, creating an overall lucid effect of awakening.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The long-term effects of moderate absinthe consumption in humans remain unknown, although herbs traditionally used to produce absinthe are reported to have both painkilling and antiparasitic properties.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Today it is known that absinthe does not cause hallucinations.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] It was once widely promoted that excessive absinthe drinking caused effects that were discernible from those associated with alcoholism, a belief that led to the coining of the term *absinthism*.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] One of the first vilifications of absinthe followed an 1864 experiment in which Magnan simultaneously exposed one guinea pig to large doses of pure wormwood vapour, and another to alcohol vapours.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The guinea pig exposed to wormwood vapour experienced convulsive seizures, while the animal exposed to alcohol did not.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Magnan would later blame the naturally occurring (in wormwood) chemical thujone for these effects.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Thujone, once widely believed to be an active chemical in absinthe, is a GABA antagonist, and while it can produce muscle spasms in large doses, there is no direct evidence to suggest it causes hallucinations.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Past reports estimated thujone concentrations in absinthe as being up to 260 mg/kg.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] As such, most traditionally crafted absinthes, both vintage and modern, fall within the current EU standards.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Tests conducted on mice to study toxicity showed an oral LD50 of about 45 mg thujone per kg of body weight, which represents far more absinthe than could be realistically consumed.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The high percentage of alcohol in absinthe would result in mortality long before thujone could become a factor.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] In documented cases of acute thujone poisoning as a result of oral ingestion, the source of thujone was not commercial absinthe, but rather non-absinthe-related sources, such as common essential oils (which may contain as much as 50% thujone).
[src:advocaat/absinthe] One study published in the *Journal of Studies on Alcohol* concluded that high doses (0.28 mg/kg) of thujone in alcohol had negative effects on attention performance in a clinical setting.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] It delayed reaction time, and caused subjects to concentrate their attention on the central field of vision.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Low doses (0.028 mg/kg) did not produce an effect noticeably different from the plain alcohol control.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] While the effects of the high dose samples were statistically significant in a double blind test, the test subjects themselves were unable to reliably identify which samples contained thujone.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] For the average 65 kg (143 lb) man, the high dose samples in the study would equate to 18.2 mg of thujone.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The EU limit of 35 mg/L of thujone in absinthe means that given the highest permitted thujone content, that individual would need to consume approximately 0.5 litres of high-proof (e.g.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] 50%+ ABV) spirit before the thujone could be metabolized to display effects detectable in a clinical setting, which would result in a potentially lethal BAC of >0.4%.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Most countries (except Switzerland) at present do not possess a legal definition of absinthe (unlike Scotch whisky or cognac).
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Accordingly, producers are free to label a product "absinthe" or "absinth", whether or not it bears any resemblance to the traditional spirit.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Absinthe is readily available in many bottle shops.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Bitters may contain a maximum 35 mg/kg thujone, while other alcoholic beverages can contain a maximum 10 mg/kg.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The domestic production and sale of absinthe is regulated by state licensing laws.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] These controls have now been repealed, and permission is no longer required.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Absinthe was prohibited in Brazil until 1999 and was brought by entrepreneur Lalo Zanini and legalised in the same year.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Presently, absinthe sold in Brazil must abide by the national law that restricts all spirits to a maximum of 54% ABV.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] While this regulation is enforced throughout channels of legal distribution, it may be possible to find absinthe containing alcohol in excess of the legal limit in some restaurants or food fairs.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] In Canada, liquor laws concerning the production, distribution, and sale of spirits are written and enforced by individual provincial government monopolies.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Each product is subject to the approval of a respective individual provincial liquor board before it can be sold in that province.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Importation is a federal matter and is enforced by the Canada Border Services Agency.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The importation of a nominal amount of liquor by individuals for personal use is permitted, provided that conditions for the individual's duration of stay outside the country are satisfied.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] In 2007, Canada's first genuine absinthe (Taboo Absinthe) was created by Okanagan Spirits Craft Distillery in British Columbia.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The European Union permits a maximum thujone level of 35 mg/kg in alcoholic beverages where *Artemisia* species is a listed ingredient, and 10 mg/kg in other alcoholic beverages.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Member countries regulate absinthe production within this framework.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The sale of absinthe is permitted in all EU countries unless they further regulate it.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The sale and production of absinthe was prohibited in Finland from 1919 to 1932; no current prohibitions exist.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The government-owned chain of liquor stores (Alko) is the only outlet that may sell alcoholic beverages containing over 8% ABV, although national law bans the sale of alcoholic beverages containing over 80% ABV.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Édouard Manet's first major painting *The Absinthe Drinker* was controversial, and was rejected by the Paris Salon in 1859.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] French producers circumvented this regulatory obstacle by labelling absinthe as *spiritueux à base de plantes d'absinthe* ('wormwood-based spirits'), with many either reducing or omitting fennel and hyssop altogether from their products.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] A legal challenge to the scientific basis of this decree resulted in its repeal (2009), which opened the door for the official French re-legalisation of absinthe for the first time since 1915.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The French Senate voted to repeal the prohibition in mid-April 2011.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] A ban on absinthe was enacted in Germany on 27 March 1923.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] In addition to banning the production of commercial trade in absinthe, the law went so far as to prohibit the distribution of printed matter that provided details of its production.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The original ban was lifted in 1981, but the use of *Artemisia absinthium* as a flavouring agent remained prohibited.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] On 27 September 1991, Germany adopted the European Community's standards of 1988, which effectively re-legalised absinthe.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The Fascist regime in 1926 banned the production, import, transport, and sale of any liquor named *Assenzio*.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The ban was reinforced in 1931 with harsher penalties for transgressors and remained in force until 1992 when the Italian government amended its laws to comply with the EU directive 88/388/EEC.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Although absinthe is not prohibited at the national level, some local authorities have banned it.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The ban came in August 2008 after several issues of misuse drew public and police attention.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] One incident resulted in breathing difficulties and hospitalising of a 17-year-old for alcohol poisoning.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The particular brand of absinthe that caused these effects was bottled at 89% ABV.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The sale and production of absinthe has never been prohibited in Sweden or Norway.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] However, the only outlet that may sell alcoholic beverages containing more than 3.5% ABV in Sweden and 4.75% ABV in Norway is the government-owned chain of liquor stores known as Systembolaget in Sweden and Vinmonopolet in Norway.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Systembolaget and Vinmonopolet did not import or sell absinthe for many years after the ban in France; however, today several absinthes are available for purchase in Systembolaget stores, including Swedish made distilled absinthe.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] In Norway, on the other hand, one is less likely to find many absinthes since Norwegian alcohol law prohibits the sale and importation of alcoholic beverages above 60% ABV, which eliminates most absinthes.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] In Switzerland, the sale and production of absinthe was prohibited from 1910 to 1 March 2005.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] This was based on a vote in 1908, inspired by the Jean Lanfray incident.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] To be legally made or sold in Switzerland, absinthe must be distilled, must not contain certain additives, and must be either naturally coloured or left uncoloured.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] In 2014, the Federal Administrative Court of Switzerland invalidated a governmental decision of 2010 which allowed only absinthe made in the Val-de-Travers region to be labelled as absinthe in Switzerland.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The court found that absinthe was a label for a product and was not tied to a geographic origin.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Absinthe was never legally prohibited in the UK, but was not imported for a 70-year period.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] In 2007, the Alcohol and Tobacco Tax and Trade Bureau (TTB) effectively lifted the long-standing absinthe ban, and it has since approved many brands for sale in the US market.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] This was made possible partly through the TTB's clarification of the Food and Drug Administration's (FDA) thujone content regulations, which specify that finished food and beverages that contain *Artemisia* species must be thujone-free.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] In this context, the TTB considers a product thujone-free if the thujone content is less than 10 ppm (equal to 10 mg/kg).
[src:advocaat/absinthe] This is verified through the use of gas chromatography–mass spectrometry.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The brands Kübler and Lucid and their lawyers did most of the work to get absinthe legalized in the U.S., over the 2004–2007 time period.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] In the U.S., 5 March sometimes is referred to as "National Absinthe Day", as it was the day the 95-year ban on absinthe was finally lifted.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Absinthe imported in violation of these regulations is subject to seizure at the discretion of U.S.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Numerous artists and writers living in France in the late 19th and early 20th centuries were noted absinthe drinkers and featured absinthe in their work.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Some of these included Édouard Manet, Guy de Maupassant, Paul Verlaine, Amedeo Modigliani, Edgar Degas, Henri de Toulouse-Lautrec, Vincent van Gogh, Oscar Wilde, Arthur Rimbaud, and Émile Zola.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Many other renowned artists and writers similarly drew from this cultural well, including Aleister Crowley, Ernest Hemingway, Pablo Picasso, August Strindberg, and Erik Satie.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] The aura of illicitness and mystery surrounding absinthe has played into literature, movies, music, and television, where it is often portrayed as a mysterious, addictive, and mind-altering drink.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Marie Corelli's *Wormwood: A Drama of Paris* (1890) was a popular novel about a Frenchman driven to murder and ruin after being introduced to absinthe.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Intended as a morality tale on the dangers of the drink, it was speculated to have contributed to subsequent bans of absinthe in Europe and the United States.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] Some of the earliest film references include *The Hasher's Delirium* (1910) by Émile Cohl, an early pioneer in the art of animation, as well as two different silent films, each titled *Absinthe*, from 1913 and 1914 respectively.
[src:advocaat/absinthe] More recently, it served as the title of a 2018 song by the indie group I Don't Know How But They Found Me.
[src:advocaat/acerum] In the 1970s, distillers began to produce alcohol from maple syrup.
[src:advocaat/acerum] Although some distilled alcohol tests were then carried out in university laboratories, it was not until the 1990s that certain maple syrup producers began to produce a wine based on this sweet resource, which was initially called Acer.
[src:advocaat/acerum] One of the first producers of Acerum was The Domaine Acer, based in Témiscouata, Quebec.
[src:advocaat/acerum] When Vallier Robert took the reins of his family maple business in 1990, he quickly saw the potential to make alcohol.
[src:advocaat/acerum] In 1996, the maple farmer was granted the first licence to produce artisanal maple-based alcoholic beverages.
[src:advocaat/acerum] He began creating several varieties of maple sap wine, including dry, sparkling and dessert wines.
[src:advocaat/acerum] During the same period, some distilleries began to market maple eau-de-vie, but it was not until December 2017 that the name Acerum appeared for the first time for a maple eau-de-vie.
[src:advocaat/acerum] As defined by the specifications of the UDSÉ, Acerum must be entirely manufactured in the province of Quebec, in Canada, with maple syrup, maple concentrate, or maple sap from Quebec maples.
[src:advocaat/advocaat] Two theories have been put out on the origins of "advocaat".
[src:advocaat/advocaat] According to several makers, such as Verpoorten and Bols, and the *Oxford Companion to Sugar and Sweets*, its origins can be traced back to "abacate", an alcoholic beverage of the indigenous people in Brazil, which was made with avocado.
[src:advocaat/advocaat] Dutch colonials of northern Brazil introduced this beverage to Europe as "advocat/advocaat".
[src:advocaat/advocaat] As avocados could not grow in northern Europe, they were replaced with egg yolk, thought to have a similar taste and consistency, and the name derived from the avocado stuck, although the drink no longer contains any.
[src:advocaat/advocaat] Cooymans started a distillery in downtown 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:advocaat/advocaat] There he developed the egg drink "advocaat".
[src:advocaat/advocaat] In 1876, the Antwerp distiller Eugen Verpoorten established a distillery in Heinsberg near Aachen, Germany, which made an egg liqueur (*Eierlikör* in German) using eggs, sugar, distilled alcohol, and other ingredients.
[src:advocaat/advocaat] Jars and wide mouth bottles of thick advocaat are sold mainly in the Netherlands and Belgium, though may be available in Germany, Austria, and South Africa.
[src:advocaat/advocaat] Further exports are of a more liquid version.
[src:advocaat/advocaat] In particular the original thick variety, i.e., without albumen, is used as a waffle, pancake or poffertjes topping, as an ingredient in ice cream, custards, pastries and similar desserts, or as an apéritif or digestif.
[src:advocaat/advocaat] The latter, possibly topped with whipped cream and then occasionally sprinkled with a touch of cocoa powder, is served in a very tiny bowl or small glass from which it is eaten by use of a teaspoon.
[src:advocaat/advocaat] In Belgian restaurants and taverns, it may be a complementary accompaniment to a coffee.
[src:advocaat/advocaat] In the export variety both parts of the eggs are used.
[src:advocaat/advocaat] A popular cocktail using advocaat is the Snowball: a mixture of advocaat, sparkling lemonade and sometimes (although this is not required) lime juice that is often consumed at Christmas time.
[src:advocaat/advocaat] Another is the Fluffy duck, made with rum.
[src:advocaat/advocaat] Another advocaat-based beverage is the Bombardino, a drink commonly found in Italian ski resorts, particularly the Italian Alps, made by mixing advocaat, brandy, and whipped cream.
[src:advocaat/advocaat] The Polish equivalent, *ajerkoniak* (German: *eier* 'eggs' and French: *cognac*), is based on vodka instead of brandy, despite what the name may suggest.
[src:advocaat/advokat] Authorization to practice as *advokat* traditionally required the candidate to graduate from law school as Candidate of Law followed by three years of employment with a law firm or other eligible institution.
[src:advocaat/advokat] In recent years, candidates have also been required to undergo training and to pass a bar examination administered by Advokatsamfundet, the Danish Bar and Law Society.
[src:advocaat/advokat] To practice law as an *advokat*, the lawyer must maintain a current membership with the Danish Bar and Law Society, which supervises its approximately 4,800 members.
[src:advocaat/advokat] Apart from paying annual dues to the association, an *advokat* must also adhere to its professional code of conduct, and may face disciplinary action as a consequence of conduct deemed unprofessional by Advokatnævnet, the Disciplinary Board.
[src:advocaat/advokat] As a result of legal reform implemented in recent years, there is no longer a monopoly held by those bearing the title *advokat* on providing most legal services in Denmark.
[src:advocaat/advokat] Any lawyer applying for membership in the Finnish Bar Association must have completed a Master of Laws degree, entitling them to hold judicial office, and must be known to be a person of integrity.
[src:advocaat/advokat] They also must have several years experience in the legal profession and other judicial duties.
[src:advocaat/advokat] Only members of the bar association are entitled to use the Swedish language professional title *advokat* (fi.
[src:advocaat/advokat] The Finnish Bar Association has about 1,570 members.
[src:advocaat/advokat] A candidate seeking permission to practice from the Supervisory Authority for Legal Services (no.
[src:advocaat/advokat] *Advokattilsynet*) is required to graduate from law school as a Candidate of Law, must be a person of integrity, must be at least 20 years of age, and must have practiced as a lawyer-in-training ("advokatfullmektig") for two years.
[src:advocaat/advokat] Furthermore, the candidate must have represented clients in at least three court cases, of which one must be a civil case of a certain length, and of which one may be replaced by an exam by a certified provider.
[src:advocaat/advokat] Only those authorized by the Supervisory Council are entitled to use the professional title *advokat* in Norway.
[src:advocaat/advokat] To a certain extent, there is a monopoly held by those bearing the title *advokat* on providing legal services in Norwegian courts of law.
[src:advocaat/advokat] A candidate seeking admittance to the Swedish Bar Association is required to graduate from law school as a Candidate of Law entitling the candidate to hold judicial office, must be a person of integrity, and must have practiced for three years.
[src:advocaat/advokat] Only members of the bar association are entitled to use the professional title *advokat* in Sweden.
[src:advocaat/advokat] The Swedish Bar Association has in excess of 4,400 members.
[src:advocaat/advokat] In principle, there is no monopoly held by those bearing the title *advokat* on providing legal services in Sweden; a person may appoint almost anyone as *ombud* (representative) whether in civil, tort or criminal proceedings.
[src:advocaat/advokat] However, if a defendant wishes to recoup expenses, the *ombud* typically needs to be an approved member of the SBA.
[src:advocaat/agave] Many plants in this genus may be considered perennial, because they require several to many years to mature and flower.
[src:advocaat/agave] However, most *Agave* species are more accurately described as monocarpic rosettes or multiannuals, since each individual rosette flowers only once and then dies; a small number of *Agave* species are polycarpic.
[src:advocaat/agave] Along with plants from the closely related genera *Yucca*, *Hesperoyucca*, and *Hesperaloe,* various *Agave* species are popular ornamental plants in hot, dry climates, as they require very little supplemental water to survive.
[src:advocaat/agave] Some *Agave* species are known by the common name "century plant".
[src:advocaat/agave] In other regions, it goes by different names.
[src:advocaat/agave] In the Chinese, Japanese, and Korean languages, it is referred to as the compound word *dragon tongue orchid* (simplified Chinese: 龙舌兰; traditional Chinese: 龍舌蘭; pinyin: *lóngshélán*; Japanese: 竜舌蘭, romanized: *ryūzetsuran*; Korean: 용설란; Hanja: 龍舌蘭; RR: *yongseollan*).
[src:advocaat/agave] In Malta, it is referred to as *Sabbara*; In Maltese, Agave americana is referred to as "Sabbara tal-Amerika", and Agave sisalana is referred to as "Sabbara ta' Sisal".
[src:advocaat/agave] The succulent leaves of most *Agave* species have sharp marginal teeth, an extremely sharp terminal spine, and are very fibrous inside.
[src:advocaat/agave] The stout stem is usually extremely short, which may make the plant appear as though it is stemless.
[src:advocaat/agave] Agaves can be confused with cacti, aloes, or stonecrops, but although these plants all share similar morphological adaptations to arid environments (e.g. succulence), each group belongs to a different plant family and probably experienced convergent evolution.
[src:advocaat/agave] Further, cactus (Cactaceae) and stonecrop (Crassulaceae) lineages are eudicots, while aloes (Asphodelaceae) and agaves (Asparagaceae) are monocots.
[src:advocaat/agave] The agave root system, consisting of a network of shallow rhizomes, allows the agave to efficiently capture moisture from rain, condensation, and dew.
[src:advocaat/agave] In addition to growing from seeds, most agaves produce 'pups' – young plants from runners.
[src:advocaat/agave] *Agave vilmoriniana* (the octopus agave) produces hundreds of pups on its bloom stalk.
[src:advocaat/agave] Agave leaves store the plant's water and are crucial to its continued existence.
[src:advocaat/agave] The coated leaf surface prevents evaporation.
[src:advocaat/agave] The leaves also have sharp, spiked edges.
[src:advocaat/agave] The spikes discourage predators from eating the plant or using it as a source of water and are so tough that ancient peoples used them for sewing needles.
[src:advocaat/agave] Some agaves bloom at a height up to 9 m (30 ft) so that they are far out of reach to animals that might attack them.
[src:advocaat/agave] Smaller species, such as *Agave lechuguilla*, have smaller bloom stalks.
[src:advocaat/agave] The genus name *Agave* come from the Ancient Greek αγαυή *agauê* from ἀγαυός *agauós* meaning "illustrious, noble" having to do with very tall flower spikes found on its many species.
[src:advocaat/agave] The genus *Agave* was erected by Carl Linnaeus in 1753, initially with four species.
[src:advocaat/agave] The first listed was *Agave americana*, now the type species.
[src:advocaat/agave] In the Cronquist system and others, *Agave* was placed in the family Liliaceae, but phylogenetic analyses of DNA sequences later showed it did not belong there.
[src:advocaat/agave] In the APG II system, *Agave* was placed in the segregated family Agavaceae.
[src:advocaat/agave] When this system was superseded by the APG III system in 2009, the Agavaceae were subsumed into the expanded family Asparagaceae, and *Agave* was treated as one of 18 genera in the subfamily Agavoideae, a position retained in the APG IV system of 2016.
[src:advocaat/agave] However, Agavaceae had regained its taxonomic status as an independent family by 2020.
[src:advocaat/agave] Agaves and close relatives have long presented significant taxonomic difficulty.
[src:advocaat/agave] These difficulties could be due to the relatively young evolutionary age of the group (major diversification events of the group most likely occurred 8–10 million years ago), ease of hybridization between species (and even genera), incomplete lineage sorting, and long generation times.
[src:advocaat/agave] Within a species, morphological variations can be considerable, especially in cultivation; many named species may be variants of original wild-type species that horticulturalists bred to appear unique in cultivation.
[src:advocaat/agave] With the advent of DNA sequencing, new karyologic and evolutionary phylogenetic studies showed that the genera *Manfreda*, *Polianthes* and *Prochnyanthes* were genetically nested within the traditional circumscription of *Agave*, rendering the genus paraphyletic.
[src:advocaat/agave] Early in the 21st century, these new phylogenetic results led to a reclassification of to include *Manfreda*, *Polianthes* and *Prochnyanthes* together as *Agave* subgenus *Manfreda*.
[src:advocaat/agave] There was reaction against the changes from those who noted that the large morphological differences between the genera in this new *Agave* s.l. making them "counter-intuitive from a horticultural point of view".
[src:advocaat/agave] *Manfreda* morphologically differs from the classic *Agave* description in being herbaceous and bulbous, while *Polianthes* are deciduous with narrow leaves and no spines.
[src:advocaat/agave] Mexican taxonomists have continued to adhere to the traditional classifications and have published new species of *Polianthes*.
[src:advocaat/agave] Thus, based on a wider consideration of previously established genetic, morphological, and estimated genetic divergence times, Vázquez-García et al. proposed a narrower circumscription of *Agave* by creating three new genera: *Echinoagave*, *Paleoagave* and *Paraagave*.
[src:advocaat/agave] These new genera have gained some acceptance, and pave the way for a reconsideration of *Manfreda*, *Polianthes* and *Prochnyanthes*.
[src:advocaat/agave] Some commonly grown species include *Agave americana*, *A. angustifolia*, *A. attenuata*, *A. murpheyi*, *A. palmeri*, *A. parryi*, *A. parviflora*, *A. tequilana*, *A. victoriae-reginae*, and *A. vilmoriniana*.
[src:advocaat/agave] One of the most familiar species is *A. americana*, a native of tropical America.
[src:advocaat/agave] Common names include century plant, *maguey* (in Mexico), or American aloe (though not related to the genus *Aloe*).
[src:advocaat/agave] The name "century plant" refers to the long time the plant takes to flower.
[src:advocaat/agave] The number of years before flowering occurs depends on the vigor of the individual plant, the richness of the soil, and the climate; during these years, the plant is storing in its fleshy leaves the nourishment required for the effort of flowering.
[src:advocaat/agave] Some species contain components in their juice which can cause dermatitis for some people.
[src:advocaat/agave] The ethnobotany of the agave was described by William H.
[src:advocaat/agave] The four major edible parts of the agave are the flowers, the leaves, the stalks or basal rosettes, and the sap (in Spanish: *aguamiel*, meaning "honey water").
[src:advocaat/agave] The sap of some species can also be used as soap.
[src:advocaat/agave] Each agave plant produces several pounds of edible flowers during its final season.
[src:advocaat/agave] The stalks, which are ready during the summer, before the blossom, weigh several pounds each.
[src:advocaat/agave] Roasted, they are sweet and can be chewed to extract the sap or *aguamiel*, like sugarcane.
[src:advocaat/agave] When dried out, the stalks can be used to make didgeridoos.
[src:advocaat/agave] The leaves may be collected in winter and spring, when the plants are rich in sap, for eating.
[src:advocaat/agave] The leaves of several species also yield fiber, for instance, *A. sisalana*, the sisal hemp, and *A. decipiens*, the false sisal hemp.
[src:advocaat/agave] *A. americana* is the source of pita fiber, and is used as a fiber plant in Mexico, the West Indies, and southern Europe.
[src:advocaat/agave] The agave, especially *A. murpheyi*, was a major food source for the prehistoric indigenous people of the Southwestern United States.
[src:advocaat/agave] The Hohokam of southern Arizona cultivated large areas of agave.
[src:advocaat/agave] The Navajo similarly found many uses for the agave plant.
[src:advocaat/agave] A beverage is squeezed from the baked fibers, and the heads can be baked or boiled, pounded into flat sheets, sun dried, and stored for future use.
[src:advocaat/agave] The baked, dried heads are also boiled and made into an edible paste, eaten whole, or made into soup.
[src:advocaat/agave] The leaves are eaten boiled, and the young, tender flowering stalks and shoots are roasted and eaten as well.
[src:advocaat/agave] The fibers are used to make rope, the leaves are used to line baking pits, and the sharp-pointed leaf tips are used to make basketry awls.
[src:advocaat/agave] During the development of the inflorescence, sap rushes to the base of the young flower stalk.
[src:advocaat/agave] Agave syrup (commonly called agave nectar), a sweetener derived from the sap, is used as an alternative to sugar in cooking, and can be added to breakfast cereals as a binding agent.
[src:advocaat/agave] Extracts from agave leaves are under preliminary research for their potential use as food additives.
[src:advocaat/agave] The sap of *A. americana* and other species is used in Mexico and Mesoamerica to produce pulque, an alcoholic beverage.
[src:advocaat/agave] The flower shoot is cut out and the sap collected and subsequently fermented.
[src:advocaat/agave] By distillation, a spirit called mezcal is prepared; one of the best-known forms of mezcal is tequila.
[src:advocaat/agave] *azul* is used in the production of tequila.
[src:advocaat/agave] *A. angustifolia* is widely used in the production of mezcal and pulque, though at least 10 other *Agave* species are also known to be used for this.
[src:advocaat/agave] Agave can be used as the raw material for industrial production of fructans as a prebiotic dietary fiber.
[src:advocaat/agave] Agave contains fructooligosaccharides, which are naturally occurring oligosaccharides that support safely subjecting peanut-allergic people to allergen immunotherapy.
[src:advocaat/agave] Resulting from its natural habitat in stressful environments, agave is under preliminary research for its potential use in germplasm conservation and in biotechnology to better anticipate the economic effects of global climate change.
[src:advocaat/agave] It may also have use as a bioethanol or bioenergy feedstock.
[src:advocaat/agave] Agave plantations have potential applications on marginal lands unsuitable for grain crops.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The city's official name is a contraction of the (archaic) Dutch *des Hertogen bosch* ('the forest of the duke').
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The duke in question was Henry I, Duke of Brabant, whose family had owned a large estate at nearby Orthen for at least four centuries.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] He founded a new town located on some forested dunes in the middle of a marsh.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] At age 26, he granted 's-Hertogenbosch city rights and the corresponding trade privileges in 1185.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] This is the traditional date given by later chroniclers; the first mention in contemporaneous sources is 1196.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] His reason for founding the city was to protect his own interests against encroachment from Gelre and Holland; from its first days, he conceived of the city as a fortress.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] It was destroyed in 1203 in a joint expedition of Gelre and Holland, but was soon rebuilt.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] Some remnants of the original city walls remain.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] In the late 14th century, a much larger wall was erected to protect the greatly expanded settled area.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] Artificial waterways were dug to serve as a city moat, through which the rivers Dommel and Aa were diverted.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch became the birthplace and home of northern Renaissance painter Hieronymus Bosch.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] Until 1520, the city flourished, becoming the second largest population centre in the territory of the present Netherlands, after Utrecht.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The city was also a center of music, and composers, such as Jheronimus Clibano, received their training at its churches.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] Others held positions there: Matthaeus Pipelare was musical director at the Confraternity of Our Lady; and renowned Habsburg copyist and composer Pierre Alamire did much of his work at 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The wars of the Reformation changed the course of the city's history.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] During the Eighty Years' War, the city took the side of the Habsburg (Catholic) authorities and thwarted a Calvinist coup.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] It was besieged several times by Prince Maurice of Orange, stadtholder of most of the Dutch Republic, who wanted to bring 's-Hertogenbosch under the rule of the rebel United Provinces.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The city was successfully defended against Prince Maurice in 1601 and again in 1603, but it eventually fell in the 1629 siege led by his brother Frederick Henry.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] In the years of Truce, before the renewed fighting after 1618, the fortifications were greatly expanded.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The surrounding marshes made a siege of the conventional type impossible, and the fortress, deemed impregnable, was nicknamed *moerasdraak*, or the Swamp Dragon.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The town was nevertheless finally conquered by Frederik Hendrik of Orange in 1629 in a typically Dutch stratagem: he diverted the rivers Dommel and Aa, created a polder by constructing a forty-kilometre (25 mile) dyke and then pumped out the water by mills.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] After a siege of three months, the city had to surrender—an enormous blow to Habsburg geo-political strategy during the Thirty Years' War.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] This surrender cut the town off from the rest of the duchy and the area was treated by the Republic as an occupation zone without political liberties (see also Generality Lands).
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] After the Peace of Westphalia, the fortifications were again expanded.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] In 1672, the Dutch *rampjaar*, the city held against the army of Louis XIV of France.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] In 1794 French revolutionary troops under the command of Charles Pichegru attacked the city.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] It was only weakly defended, and fell after a short siege.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] Pichegru then crossed the rivers and put an end to the Dutch Republic.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] Under the new Batavian Republic, established in 1795, both Catholics and *Brabanders* at last gained equal rights.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] From 1806, the city became part of the Kingdom of Holland and from 1810, it was incorporated into the First French Empire.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] It was captured by the Prussians in 1814.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The next year, 1815, when the United Kingdom of the Netherlands was established, it became the capital of North Brabant.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] Many newer and more modern fortresses were created in the vicinity of the city.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] A new canal was built, the 'Zuid-Willemsvaart', which gave the city an economic impulse.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] Until 1878, it was forbidden to build outside the ramparts.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] That led to overcrowding and the highest infant mortality in the kingdom.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] At the end of the 19th century, the very conservative city government prevented industrial investment to avoid an increase in the number of workers and the establishment of educational institutions: students were regarded as disorderly.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] As a result, the relative importance of the city diminished.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] One of the few official Nazi concentration camp complexes in Western Europe outside Germany and Austria was named after 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] It operated from January 1943, to September 1944 and was known to the Germans as Herzogenbusch (see List of subcamps of Herzogenbusch).
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] About 30,000 inmates were interned in the complex during this time, of whom about 12,000 were Jews.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] In the Netherlands, this camp is known as 'Kamp Vught', because the concentration camp was actually located at a heath near Vught, a village a few kilometres south of 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The city was occupied by German forces during World War II from 1940 to 1944.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The railway station was bombed by planes of the Royal Air Force on 16 September 1944.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The city was liberated between 24 and 27 October 1944 during Operation Pheasant by British soldiers of Major-General Robert Knox Ross's 53rd (Welsh) Infantry Division following the victory of the 1st Battalion, East Lancashire Regiment, of 158th Infantry Brigade over the enemy on 23–24 October.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] After the war, 's-Hertogenbosch was modernized, like many other cities in the Netherlands.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] It was possible that it was only the geography that shielded the old town from rigorous reconstruction in those early years.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] Just in time, the pendulum swung back to protecting the history of the city.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] In 1956, the council wanted to demolish the Moriaan, the oldest brick building in the Netherlands, to give traffic better access to the market square.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The permit was refused by the government and instead the building was restored, starting in 1963.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] Later, city councils became much more aware of the value of historic buildings and from about the turn of the millennium, the historic fortifications are also given much attention by the authorities.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The population centres in the municipality are: Bokhoven, Crevecoeur, Deuteren (former village), Dieskant, Empel, Engelen, Gewande, 's-Hertogenbosch, Hintham, Kruisstraat, Maliskamp, Meerwijk, Orthen (former village), Oud-Empel, and Rosmalen.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] Climate in this area has mild differences between highs and lows, and there is adequate rainfall year-round.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The Köppen Climate Classification subtype for this climate is "Cfb" (Marine West Coast Climate/Oceanic climate).
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The city of 's-Hertogenbosch has become a center of industry, education, administration and culture.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] It is currently the fourth city of North Brabant.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] It is home to many national and international businesses such as Heineken, Epic, Tyco International, SAP and many others.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The Jeroen Bosch Hospital is the biggest employer in the area, with over 4,000 employees.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] There are also over 350 restaurants, pubs and cafés to be found in the city.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch is also home to the European Ceramic Work Centre.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] This is a juried international ceramic residency where they invite artists, designers and architects from around to the world to explore the medium of Ceramics.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] This program was initially started in 1991 and continues to this day.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The city has its own food speciality, the Bossche Bol—effectively a giant profiterole, somewhat larger than a tennis ball, which is filled with whipped cream and coated with chocolate.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The spoken language is Maaslands (the variant spoken in 's-Hertogenbosch is called *Bosch* which is placed among the Central North Brabantian dialects, although other classification systems also describe it as East Brabantian), which is very similar to colloquial Dutch.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] De Toonzaal is a music venue for chamber music, improvised music, and experimental music.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] For popular music there is the venue W2 (or Willem II).
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The Noordbrabants Museum is a provincial museum with an overview of works that Vincent van Gogh made in Brabant.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The Design Museum Den Bosch is a modern art museum.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The Jheronimus Bosch Art Center, is dedicated to the work of Hieronymus Bosch.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] Other museums include the Swan Brothers' House and Museum Slager.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] Also the National (Dutch) Carnavalsmuseum Oeteldonks gemintemuzejum is located in the city.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] In the near future a new museum will be opened about the fortresses of the town and in general in Europe.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The house where the famous painter Hieronymus produced his paintings can be visited on the market square.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch has a strong carnival tradition.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] In its current form the story and symbolism dates from 1881 to 1883.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] In these years some citizens created the legend of "Oeteldonk", whereby the city was renamed to Oeteldonk for the three day carnival.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] "Donk" is a reference to a dry place in the marsh.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The frog is widely used as a symbol during the 's-Hertogenbosch Carnival.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] It is also a symbol of the Oeteldonk marsh.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] It was also a remark aimed at Bishop Godschalk from Den Dungen, where 'Van den Oetelaar' was a common family name.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] He had wanted to forbid the traditional festivities of Shrove Tuesday that often led to excesses.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] Oeteldonk is a village and therefore every inhabitant is a farmer or a '*durske*' (a girl or young woman), eliminating class differences.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The village is headed by the Mayor "Peer vaan den Muggenheuvel tot den Bobberd".
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] Each year the mayor of 's-Hertogenbosch hands over his authority to the Mayor of Oeteldonk.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] On Sunday at 11:11 AM the Mayor of Oeteldonk then receives Prince Carnaval "Prince Amadeiro XXVI" at Oeteldonk central station.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] From there a parade of all carnival clubs escorts the company to the town hall.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The citizens of 's-Hertogenbosch wear traditional outfits throughout these days.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] A so-called *boerenkiel* is worn and every year patches are designed according to that years theme which can then be stitched onto the outfit.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The *boerenkiel* is often combined with a traditional farmers bandana and a long scarf in the colors of Oeteldonk.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The tradition of the Boerenkiel and / or Bandana is very different from the carnival traditions in the rest of the Netherlands.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] Other aspects like the parade, the temporary name and the temporary flag (for Oeteldonk red, white and yellow) are very similar.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch was founded as a fortified city and that heritage can still be seen today.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] After World War II, plans were made to modernise the old city, by filling in the canals, removing or modifying some ramparts and redeveloping historic neighbourhoods.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] Before these plans could come to effect, the central government declared the city a protected townscape.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] Most historic elements have been preserved.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] In contrast to cities like Rotterdam, 's-Hertogenbosch also survived the Second World War relatively unscathed.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] Much of its historic heritage remains intact, and today there are always renovations going on in the city to preserve the many old buildings, fortifications, churches and statues for later generations.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The city center has a cosy atmosphere because of the almost continuous ramparts that still surround it.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] It has been molded by the multiple rivers that convene on 's-Hertogenbosch, giving the center its strange street plan so different from the usual grid plan where streets meet at right angles.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The center is dominated by Saint John's Cathedral (*Sint-Janskathedraal* in Dutch), which dates from c.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] 1220 and is best known for its Brabantine Gothic design and the many sculptures of craftsmen that are sitting on almost every arc and rim along the outside of the cathedral.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] In 2010 an extensive restoration was completed, undoing the damage of many years of wear-and-tear and acid rain.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] On the central square is the oldest remaining brick house of the Netherlands, 'de Moriaan', which was built at the beginning of the 13th century.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] In the 1960s, de Moriaan was renovated to its former glory based on a famous 16th-century Dutch painting called 'De Lakenmarkt van 's-Hertogenbosch' ('The fabric market of 's-Hertogenbosch').
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The town hall is an original 14th-century Gothic building.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] After the town was conquered by the Dutch Republic in 1629, it received a new facade in the style of Dutch Baroque architecture.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] It showcased the authority of the new masters, just like the new town hall in Maastricht would.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] Hidden below the old city is a canal network called the Binnendieze, which once spanned 22 km (14 mi).
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] It started out as a regular river, the Dommel, running through the city in medieval times.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] Due to a lack of space in the city, people started building their houses and roads over the river.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] Later, the Binnendieze functioned as a sewer and fell into disrepair.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] In recent decades, the remaining sixth part of the old waterway system has been renovated, and it is possible to take several guided subterranean boat trips through it.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch has an extensive and almost complete fifteenth-to-seventeenth-century city fortification.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] It was made to profit from the city's strong defensive position, lying on a sandy hill in the center of a large swamp fed by many rivers.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] This also caused the main ramparts to be preserved, because they were crucial in keeping out the water.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] In 2004 the city was awarded the title *European Fortress City of the year*.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] In the years that followed it restored many of the city defenses to much of their old glory.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] Apart from small sections of medieval walls, the main structure of the fortification is a late-medieval (fifteenth-century) wall.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The upper sections were removed when cannon became more powerful, and polygonal bastions were added, some after the conquest by the republic.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] Most of these have not been restored to their original height, but do maintain their brick walls.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The citadel in the north west of the city does retain its original height.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] Around the city itself many other fortresses can still be seen.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] In the north east of the old city, the hexagonal gunpowder magazine, called *Kruithuis* is located close to the citadel.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] It is one of only a handful that still exist in the Netherlands, and was built when the city was still part of the Spanish Netherlands.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] It is planned to become the museum of fortress 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] One of the bastions of the fortress now houses the mini museum Bastionder.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] It has been dug out in a bastion of the south side.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] On the inside it shows a unique wrought iron cannon, and an older bastion that was walled in by the current one.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] On the south side of the city, the city center and walls still border the Bossche Broek, an old polder that could never be made dry.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] In 1995 the dyke of the Dommel broke and an enormous amount of water entered the polder.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] It also flooded and blocked the main Dutch highway A2.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] In order to prevent this in the future, the area was rearranged to store excess water in case of emergencies.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] In 2006 the area had been furnished with higher dikes and locks that allowed a controlled flooding of the polder and some adjacent areas in case of emergency.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The Bossche Broek is now a 22-hectare (54-acre) nature reserve, that stretches all the way to Vught.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] It is connected to the Moerputten and Vlijmens Ven, with which it forms a Natura 2000 area.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] Rare species in the area are the scarce large blue and the European weather loach.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The Moerputten sports the Moerputten Bridge, a 600-metre (650 yard) long nineteenth century railway bridge and engineering feat.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] What is unique about the area is its close proximity to the city center.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The city is also the location of the *Bolwoningen* complex, an array of fifty experimental spherical houses designed by Dries Kreijkamp.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The Lutheran Church, 's-Hertogenbosch is no longer used as a church.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The city has one professional football club, FC Den Bosch.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] It is the 1967 successor of the professional branches of BVV (Bossche Voetbal Vereniging) and Wilhelmina.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] Both of them still exist as amateur football clubs.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] As a successor of BVV FC Den Bosch can claim the national championship of 1948.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] This championship led to the construction of stadium De Vliert, which at one time had a capacity of 30,000.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] Due to the less successful years that followed, the capacity is now only 8,500 visitors.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] FC Den Bosch was the first club of Dutch international player Ruud van Nistelrooy.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch is more successful in field hockey.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The women's team in particular is a dominant force in the Dutch field hockey competition.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The professional basketball club Heroes Den Bosch is also very successful.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The city's rugby club is called The Dukes and dates from 1974.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] It is located at a very scenic location at the foot of the city walls.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] Because of the limited space, the club plays on artificial turf and part of the accommodation is subterranean.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] It became the national rugby champion in 2008.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] As regards events the city is host to the Rosmalen Grass Court Championships, a combined ATP Tour and WTA Tour grass court tennis event played two weeks before the Wimbledon Championships.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The World Archery Championships and World Para Archery Championship were held here in June 2019.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] During these combined World Championships two separate venues were used: the Parade and the rugby fields of The Dukes.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] All finals took place in the arena at the Parade.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The Parade is a historic square surrounded by high trees, situated at the foot of the nearly seven-hundred-year-old Saint John's Cathedral in the attractive center of 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The Zuid-Willemsvaart runs from the Meuse just north of the city towards Maastricht via Helmond and Weert.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] In 's-Hertogenbosch it runs through the city proper, south east from where a bastion has been cut off from the citadel.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] Because of this route it was impossible to widen it further than for ships of CEMT class II.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] Therefore, the Máxima Canal of 8 km (5 miles) was dug just east of the city, creating a shortcut from the canal to the Meuse suitable for ships of CEMT class IV.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] On the remaining part of the Zuid-Willemsvaart west of the city is the industrial harbor of 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch is situated on the busy A2 motorway, the most important north–south connection of the Netherlands.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] This connection was established with the opening of the Dieze Bridge in 1942.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] From 1961 the Utrecht-'s-Hertogenbosch section was 2 times 2 lanes.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] In 1970 the A2 was rerouted to the east of the city.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] In 1989 it finally became a controlled-access highway.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] In 1996 the section between 's-Hertogenbosch and Eindhoven became a controlled-access highway.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The situation in Maastricht was only solved in 2016, when the Koning Willem-Alexandertunnel was opened.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] On the east–west axis 's-Hertogenbosch is on the A59 motorway.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The A65 motorway between 's-Hertogenbosch and Tilburg is a regional highway, but is not completely access-controlled.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch railway station is on the Utrecht–Boxtel part of the railway stretch between Amsterdam and the Dutch industrial/tech center near Eindhoven.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] As a consequence north–south trains depart every ten minutes.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] On the Tilburg–Nijmegen railway trains run on a more modest schedule.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch railway station is also a major station for Arriva buslines that serve the city and most of its suburbs.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] Other stations within the limits of the municipality are 's-Hertogenbosch Oost railway station and Rosmalen railway station.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] Vught railway station is actually closer to the city center than that in Rosmalen.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch has attempted to adapt to the growing popularity of the bicycle in Dutch cities.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] A reasonable amount of bike paths has so far been constructed in the town.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] In 2011, the city was chosen as *Fietsstad 2011*—the top bike city of the Netherlands for 2011.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] This is a big achievement for a city where bicycle use is lower than in the rest of the Netherlands".
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] 's-Hertogenbosch has multiple vocational universities called *Hogeschool* in Dutch.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The HAS Hogeschool of about 3,500 students is focused on agricultural and food technology.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] Avans Hogeschool is located in 's-Hertogenbosch and two nearby cities.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] Joost is an art academy that is now part of Avans and dates back to 1812.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] Fontys Hogeschool also offers some education in the city.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The Jheronimus Academy of Data Science (JADS), located at the Mariënburg Campus in the center of 's-Hertogenbosch, and provides a number of data science programs at graduate (MSc) and post-graduate level (PhD).
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] It is a department of the Eindhoven University of Technology and Tilburg University.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] In secondary education the City Gymnasium is a gymnasium (school) that originated from the Latin school of the city.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] It is comparable to a grammar school and can trace its origin back 1274.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The same type of education and all other types of secondary education are offered by a number of large institutes.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] Roman Catholicism is the dominant religion in 's-Hertogenbosch, with somewhat more than 40% of the population counting themselves as belonging to it.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] Even so, attendance at mass is significantly lower than 40%.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] Three churches in the city center are still in use by the Catholic church: Saint John's Cathedral, Saint Catherine and the Monastery Church of the Franciscans nearby the railway station.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] Smaller churches in use by the Roman Catholic church are: Saint Anne's Church in Hintham, Saint Landoline Church in Empel, Saint Willibrord Church in Maaspoort, Saint Lambert Church (Rosmalen), etc.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The Protestant religion has seen its share of believers in the city fall from 20% to about 4%.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The Eastern Orthodox Church is a new church in town.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] It is based at Saint Catherine's Church where Catholic worship services have been held again since 2021.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The Arrahma Mosque has been built by the Moroccan community.
[src:advocaat/s-hertogenbosch] The Turkish community has the Orhan Gazi Mosque.
